  <h2 class="section-title"><span>FAQs</span></h2>
  <div class="faq-container">
    <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">Who can donate blood?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">Most people can donate blood if they are in good health. You need to be at least 17 years old, weigh at least 110 pounds, and not be anemic.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">How often can I donate blood?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">You can donate whole blood every 56 days. Platelet donations can be made more frequently, up to every 7 days, but no more than 24 times a year.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">What should I do before donating blood?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">Get a good night's sleep, eat a healthy meal, and drink plenty of fluids. Avoid fatty foods before donating.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
        <div class="faq-question">What happens to my blood after donation?</div>
        <div class="faq-answer">Your blood is tested for various infections and diseases. If it's safe, it will be separated into components (red cells, plasma, platelets) and used to help patients in need.</div>
    </div>
